# Sockets

```elixir
Mix.install([
  {:sockets, "~> 2.1"}
])
```

## Getting started

`sockets` is a wrapper library over built-in Erlang's modules `gen_tcp`, `gen_udp`, `gen_sctp`, `ssl` and on top of that it also implements support for `RFC 6455 WebSockets` and `SOCKS`. Its API allows you to easily build both clients and servers handling data exchange over the socket.

The easiest and most convenient way to start using the library is to use methods available in `Socket` module.

Here is a quick and simple example how to establish an **SSL** connection with the web server at `example.com`:

```elixir
{:ok, client} = Socket.connect("ssl://example.com")
client |> Socket.Stream.send("GET / HTTP/1.1\r\nHost: example.com\r\n\r\n")
client |> Socket.Stream.recv!()
```

**NOTE:** the URI used in this example starts with `ssl://...` instead of more familiar `https://...` scheme.

The reason for this is to delibrately make a distinction that the library operates on the transport layer rather than overloading `http://` or `https://` with transport-level meaning.

The library uses explicit URI schemes that map directly to the underlying protocol. `tcp://` and `udp://` correspond to `gen_tcp` and `gen_udp`, `ssl://` corresponds to `:ssl` making TLS explicit up front, and `ws://` or `wss://` follow the conventions established by **RFC 6455 WebSockets**.

This makes intent clear at the call site — the scheme tells you not just where to connect, but exactly which protocol is being used.

<!-- livebook:{"break_markdown":true} -->

Here is an example how to connect to a non-secure websocket endpoint at `ws://echo.websocket.in`:

```elixir
socket = Socket.connect!("ws://echo.websocket.in")
socket |> Socket.Web.send!({:text, "text"})
socket |> Socket.Web.recv!()
```

And this is an example how to connect to a secure websocket endpoint at `wss://echo.websocket.in`:

```elixir
socket = Socket.connect!("wss://echo.websocket.in")
socket |> Socket.Web.send!({ :text, "test" })
socket |> Socket.Web.recv!()
```
